  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical buzzword—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects anyone who's ever felt their identity might undermine their performance. Growing up in Chicago with parents who only went as far as lower secondary and a vocational diploma, I've seen firsthand how education can feel like a second chance, especially when you're not from a traditional academic background. When I was a kid, my dad would joke about how he couldn't understand calculus because he was a plumber—something I now recognize as a classic case of stereotype threat. The idea that your group identity might make you underperform is powerful, but it's not just about being labeled 'bad at math.' It's about the psychological weight of expectations that can paralyze you in the moment. As someone curious and open-minded, I think we should address this head-on, not through grand policies alone but by creating environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes. In my plumbing job, I've noticed that even the most skilled technicians often struggle when they're under pressure to 'prove' themselves. If we could normalize the idea that it's okay to be confused or to ask questions without judgment, STEM would be more accessible. The key is to shift the narrative from 'you must be smart enough' to 'you have the potential to learn.' This isn't about fixing people—it's about fixing the system so that everyone has a fair shot to contribute without the fear of failing because of who they are.",
